1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,500
Two coding agents can edit different files and still implement the same behavior.

2
00:00:08,500 --> 00:00:18,750
Runway compares planned scope before either starts, guards Codex patches, then verifies the final diff.

3
00:00:18,750 --> 00:00:30,400
This is not a fake agent swarm. A public issue produced three human implementations and two duplicate closures.

4
00:00:30,400 --> 00:00:42,070
That proves the failure shape, not agent prevalence. Official Codex guidance separately names conflict risk.

5
00:00:42,070 --> 00:00:53,700
Pricing is airborne. Tax declares the same file, exported symbol, and pricing behavior, so Runway holds it.

6
00:00:53,700 --> 00:01:05,380
Reroute Tax, then reserve it. Checkout stays a caution: an import is evidence, not proof of conflict.

7
00:01:05,380 --> 00:01:15,900
The native Codex hook denies an undeclared patch before execution. The declared Tax file passes.

8
00:01:15,900 --> 00:01:26,400
It guards supported Codex patch tools; it is not a universal write sandbox.

9
00:01:26,400 --> 00:01:38,700
The focused test passes, but a fresh Git audit finds drift, so no handoff exists.

10
00:01:38,700 --> 00:01:51,090
Remove only the drift and verify again. Runway records executed proof before issuing a portable receipt.

11
00:01:51,090 --> 00:02:01,100
Two commands install the skill, hook, and standalone CLI without rebuilding.

12
00:02:01,100 --> 00:02:11,210
The replay fingerprint verifies. Thirty-nine tests cover collisions, concurrency, drift, denial, traversal, and parity.

13
00:02:11,210 --> 00:02:21,500
GPT-5.6 ran through Codex to build and pressure-test the parser, plugin, hook, CLI, protocol, UI, and tests.

14
00:02:21,500 --> 00:02:31,800
Runtime decisions stay deterministic. Runway acts before, during, and after code, with evidence at every boundary.
